âœ… Function â€“ Do Some Work and Return
Letâ€™s say we want to process something and get a result back. Thatâ€™s where Function comes in.

It takes one input and returns one output.

Function<Integer, Integer> square = n -> n * 10;
System.out.println(square.apply(5)); // Output: 50
ğŸ”— Chain the Function
You can combine multiple functions using andThen() and compose().

Function<Integer, Integer> multiply = x -> x * 2;
Function<Integer, Integer> add = x -> x + 3;

System.out.println(multiply.andThen(add).apply(5)); // (5*2) + 3 = 13
System.out.println(multiply.compose(add).apply(5)); // (5+3) * 2 = 16
Just remember:

andThen: first do this, then that.

compose: first that, then this.

ğŸ›ï¸ Consumer â€“ Take It, Do Something, No Return
Imagine going to a shop. You give your money (input), and they give you a product (output).

In Consumer, you just give input and they do something â€” but nothing is returned.

Consumer<String> greet = name -> System.out.println("Welcome " + name);
greet.accept("Noormohamed");
Just use accept(), no return.

Think like: â€œI gave input, they did their job, I donâ€™t care what happens after.â€

ğŸ“¦ Supplier â€“ Just Give Me Something
Now reverse the story â€” You are waiting in a shop, expecting a free product. You donâ€™t give anything, but you get something in return.

Thatâ€™s the job of Supplier. It doesnâ€™t take any argument but just returns a value.

