Use test() method.

Think: ask a question, get yes or no.

ğŸ¤ Some Extra Members in the Family
Java also has some upgraded versions:

BiFunction
It takes two inputs, and returns one output.

BiFunction<Integer, Integer, Integer> add = (a, b) -> a + b;
System.out.println(add.apply(5, 3)); // 8
BiConsumer
It takes two inputs, and does something, but returns nothing.

BiConsumer<String, Integer> printAge = (name, age) ->
    System.out.println(name + " is " + age + " years old");

printAge.accept("Noormohamed", 24);
No return. Just do some action and finish.

ğŸ§  Final Recap â€“ The Human Way
Letâ€™s imagine you go to a store. Think like this:

Function: You give an item and they process it, like converting dollars to rupees.

Consumer: You give something, they act on it â€” like putting trash in a bin.

Supplier: You get something for free â€” like getting a chocolate sample at a shop.

Predicate: You ask: â€œIs this available?â€ â€“ they say Yes/No.

BiFunction: You give two items, they return one â€” like adding sugar and coffee, and getting coffee mix.

BiConsumer: You give two items, they act on it â€” like giving two ingredients and seeing someone cook.

âœ… Conclusion
